73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.10f90de8-05e0-4a51-b6e3-5cdbc8e92039.prompt=Datacenter\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.236feff9-01c6-41b4-8123-45c4bfc210db.prompt=Virtual Machine\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.293b1e6a-9655-491b-b248-c4c7881ade46.prompt=VMWare Host\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.31ba1fd1-b84b-4f0b-9188-c76ebeabd791.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.
73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.3bdaf313-1a13-4f09-9d49-04ccb8685749.prompt=Identify VM by\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.41d9e1e2-d4ff-4f9e-b270-8e05a2cef3c1.prompt=Enter a value for value1 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.42490d2b-bc88-49bf-a38b-e1e134f7bbbd.prompt=Virtual Machine\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.637bd158-d642-4542-b4a1-497188c5f2ef.description=
Retrieves information about a guest os running in a virtual machine. VM tools must be running on the guest to retrieve this information.

Inputs\:
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - VMware username.
    password - VMware user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type 
Valid values\: "inventorypath", "name", "ip", "hostname", "uuid", "vmid"
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output.  Descriptive result of the operation.  Reason for error on failure.
    state - Running state of the guest operating system.   Possible values\: running, shuttingdown, resetting, standby, notrunning, unknown
    hostname - Hostname of the guest according to the guest operating system.
    ipAddress - Primary IP address of the guest according to the guest operating system.  Example value\: 10.11.22.33
    guestOsId - Guest operating system identifier (short name).  Example value\: "windows7Server64Guest"
    guestOsDescription - Guest operating system full name.  Example value\: "Microsoft Windows Server 2008 R2 (64-bit)"
    guestFamily - Guest operating system family.  Example value\: "WindowsGuest "
    guestNicInfo - A json array of json objects describing the network interfaces of the guest.  Each json object has three keys\: 
macaddress - Mac address of the guest nic.  Example value\: 00\:50\:56\:87\:01\:93
ipAddresses - A json array of ip addresses assigned to the nic.  Example value\: ["fe80\:\:9802\:e33\:4e2\:2caf%15","16.93.30.83"]
network - The name of the network port group the nic is attached to.
    guestDiskInfo - A json array of json objects describing the disks attached to the guest.  Each json object has three keys\:
diskPath - The mount point of the disk on the guest.  Example value\: "C\:\"
capacity - Size of the disk in bytes.
freespace - Amount of freespace on the disk in bytes. 

Notes\:
Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.
73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.69eaa8bc-077f-4bf6-b092-4c10fee2fac7.prompt=Enter a value for array 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.69f31839-2d16-46fb-8c67-6dfb02ac1f5c.prompt=Number of seconds to sleep\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.6c300b57-bb9c-4472-865b-74f82f41ad0e.prompt=Enter a value for object 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.6ceb6765-c9c4-436a-827d-6c0c673843a8.description=
Iterates through a JavaScript array, i.e. a string value that contains an array
in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON).  Each time that this operation
is called it places the value of the current array element into the Result
output and advances the iterator to the array element.

The JSON format is basically a way to encode arrays and other values using
JavaScript notation.  For arrays, this means that the values need to be
surrounded by square brackets, and each element in the array can be a string
(which needs surrounding quotes), a number, true, false, null, or a nested array
or object.  Commas are always used as delimiters between array elements, and
they can appear within string elements without confusion.  For example, the
following is a simple JSON array\:
   [ "cat", "dog", "horse" ]
Note that the equivalent OO list would be 
   cat,dog,horse
The benefits of JavaScript arrays are that delimiters are fixed and cannot be
confused with data, and that complex nesting of arrays and objects are
supported.  The description of the enclosing folder, /Library/Utility
Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and the JSON format
is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Modifying the contents of the array during iteration is not generally supported,
but will be safe as long as the affected item(s) are beyond the current position
of the iterator.  The iterator keeps track of where it is in the array by
position.  If items are added or removed to the list in a position preceding the
iterator, it may cause the iterator to return results that are not obvious.  For
example, if the array contains [ "a", "b", "c" ] and the iterator is positioned
on the second element, "b" and the first element is removed, then the iterator
will now be at the last element in the list, "c".

There is currently a limitation that a flow can only have one of these array
iterator steps active at a time without causing possible conflicts.  In other
words, if you need to iterate through a nested array, you will should use a
sub-flow to process the inner array.  You may have two or more of these array
iterators in the same flow as long as each iterator reaches the end of its array
before the next one begins.

Inputs

   array
      The JavaScript array that will be iterated through.  The operation will
      return a failure if the array is not a JavaScript array; a normal OO list
      is NOT a JavaScript array.

Responses

   has more
      The iterator has not yet reached the end of the array. The Result output
      will be populated with the value of the current element in the array, and
      the iterator will advance to the next element in the array.

   no more
      The iterator has reached the end of the array, and there is no more data
      to return.  The iterator will become undefined after this call, which
      basically will reset it so that if called again, this operation will begin
      another iteration at the beginning of the array.

   failure
      There was some error in iterating through the list, and the Result output
      will contain information about the error.  This will occur if the input
      array is not a valid JavaScript array.  For example, if presented with a
      common list value such as a,b,c it will fail because it lacks the
      enclosing brackets and the quotes around each string element.  You may
      wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose
      problems with JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   Result
      The current array element.  When incorporating this operation into a flow,
      you should assign a meaningful result value from this field.  Note that
      since JavaScript arrays may contain nested arrays or other objects, the
      value returned in Result may also require further processing.
73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.710e7360-3439-497e-aecf-61b7072d1f97.prompt=Identify VM by\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.778be47b-7a40-4bec-9100-b52d91b3a133.prompt=Password\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.78c3d407-b83d-444f-83e0-2a7674bd2f68.prompt=Datacenter\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.8ba9a96b-1986-46f7-a983-6b77d4e45d83.prompt=VMWare User\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.8c3b6bf8-756e-4d6f-9968-d72a19806d67.prompt=VMWare User\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.a0a5e52c-f8fc-4387-a5f2-30620a53e283.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.a302c8b5-830e-421c-ac52-b1c445f04007.description=
Checks if a number or word is equal to another number or word. Word comparison is case-sensitive in alphabetical order.

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
value1 \=\= value2

Responses\:
success - The boolean operation was evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.
73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.ac0a58e0-5335-4338-8662-fc680d51f0fb.prompt=Password\: 73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.b28872eb-09bf-415e-b3d2-47de734520ea.description=
Determines the number of elements in the given JavaScript array.  If an element
is itself another JavaScript array, it only counts as 1 element; in other
words, it will not expand and count embedded arrays.  Null values are also
considered to be an element.

Examples\:
    The size of [ "apple", "banana" ] is 2.

    The size of [ "apple", "pencil", [ 0, 3, 5, -199 ] ] is 3.

    The size of [ "apple", null, "banana", null ] is 4.

    The size of [] is 0.

The description of the enclosing folder describes the JSON format with examples,
and the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   array
      The JavaScript array whose elements will be counted.  The operation will
      return a failure if the array is not a JavaScript array; a normal OO list
      is NOT a JavaScript array.

Responses

   success
      The array is a valid JavaScript array, and the Result output will be
      populated with the count of elements in the array.

   failure
      The array input does not contain a valid JavaScript array.  Result
      will contain a message to that effect.  This will occur if the input
      array is not a valid JavaScript array.  For example, if presented with a
      common list value such as a,b,c it will fail because it lacks the
      enclosing brackets and the quotes around each string element.  You may
      wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose
      problems with JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   Result
      The number of elements in the array.  Elements that are themselves arrays
      only count as a single element.
73bc6a86-7b70-4a8b-9455-93653713a70c.d38f04b6-8a80-4be6-8285-b577caedc8e7.description=
Sleeps for the number of seconds specified in the input.

Inputs\:
seconds - The number of seconds to sleep.

Responses\:
success - Slept for the number of seconds given as input.
failure - Was unable to sleep for some reason.
